Subsidy trap
The US policy of subsidizing food and energy is one that best illustrates the stark contrast between good economics and good politics.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming a core issue faced by three of the world's most important new leaders, Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Jokowi, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Italy will need to do better than expected to cut subsidies.
On the contrary, Modi is facing an even bleaker situation than expected, and may even torpedo the long-awaited WTO agreement.
The situation facing Sokuvi remains unclear.
In July, Si Seccombe completed the achievement that few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East could achieve: he significantly reduced the long-standing energy subsidies, causing prices to rise by 41-78%.
It was surprising that almost no counter-protests took place.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs more than $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have been kept at an extremely low level, to the extent that it is often used to feed animals.
In the past, North African countries' efforts to cut such subsidies often led to unrest, and even toppled governments.
But the government of Seis Ilha seems to have made some progress in this area as well.
The bread subsidy has been reduced by 13%.
There is no other choice but this.
Even after the subsidy reduction, the current government's next fiscal year's budget deficit target still reached 10% of GDP (would have reached 14% without subsidy cut).
However, few people had anticipated that the chaotic Modi could act faster than Xi in a volatile political environment.  Modi swept to power in India with an overwhelming democratic majority, eager to push through far-reaching economic reforms.
In Indonesia, President Joko Widodo has inherited a long-standing fuel subsidy, costing around $21 billion annually, equivalent to 20% of the government's expenditure, which has bankrupted the country.
Former President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono's successor, Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, took a brave first step a year ago by raising fuel prices.
Joko Widodo's advisors suggested cutting the remaining subsidies, and he bluntly said that the plan would be implemented gradually over four years.
Economists are confident in opposing commodity subsidies because the agricultural and energy markets are nearly perfectly competitive, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In the imperfectly competitive field, it is government – not large private monopolies – that is the root.
Critics of the invisible hand argue that a self-regulating private market may malfunction in various ways.
For instance, income inequality and environmental externalities are two major reasons for government intervention.
What sparks sharp controversy over subsidies for food and fossil fuels is that they are often implemented under the banner of the environment or equality, but ultimately have no impact on these goals, and often have the opposite effect.
Only about 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies have fattened the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, only less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies went to the poorest population, whereas 52.6% flowed into the pockets of the richest group.
Globally, less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Subsidies for food and energy may also distort public policy, as Modi's government, which aims to protect Indian agricultural subsidies, clearly shows.
In fact, the Modi government vetoed the WTO compromise, thereby destroying the most important progress in the multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Subsidies to farmers sometimes benefit consumers, especially in poor countries; and sometimes benefit farmers, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to achieve both.
As a result, India achieved a remarkable feat: supplying wheat to consumers at a people-friendly price, while also experiencing surpluses because farmers were getting high prices.
Farmers also receive subsidies through agricultural inputs - electricity, water and fertilizers, while the environment is damaged.
The government purchased large quantities of spoiled rice and wheat, but the distribution of what little was given to consumers was corrupt and failed to achieve its intended goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and stockpiling.
But it knew that this would violate World Trade Organization rules.
Since it was impossible to change these rules permanently, Modi simply vetoed the Trade Facilitation Agreement that the World Trade Organization had been eagerly awaiting.
Once the subsidy is put into effect, it will be very difficult to withdraw it.
When global commodity prices rise (as they did over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot insulate them from the shock.
But people who are accustomed to fixed food and energy prices will demand the government to be held accountable.
This constitutes a very strong argument, and from the very beginning, subsidies should not have been implemented.
But this does not mean that as soon as subsidies are implemented, maintaining subsidies is always the best choice for shrewd politicians.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents may also erupt.
Similarly, if the ever-widening gap ultimately leads to even higher retail prices, slow-acting leaders will not be able to benefit.
Under ideal circumstances, other more efficient measures to support the bottom line income should be taken at the same time of reducing food and energy subsidies.
Developing countries have gained significant learning experiences in effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades, Brazil's Bolsa Família, and India's Unique Identification system, etc., which involve conditional cash transfer innovations and technological innovations.
But some countries only adjusted their budget when a crisis arrived, and they may not have had the means to use transfers to alleviate the suffering.
A shrewd politician may well have to implement unpopular adjustments at the outset of their tenure.
Sukhoi and Sisu both adopted this policy.
Modi, who won a landslide victory in elections under the banner of market reform, has fallen behind.
